The Question

  • A university has two dormitories with two different cafeteria menus. We want to know:
    • How do students' weights change over the course of their first year at university?

What is the effect of the different menus on student weight change?

  • Students in the two dormitories are weighed at the beginning and end of the school year:

    • Blue points/ellipse represent students in Sex B, gold represent Sex A.
    • The dashed line is the diagonal: slope of 1 and intercept of 0.

    Two statisticians analyze these data.

    Anova

    • The first compares the mean and variance of the initial vs. final weights in each of the two dorms
      • In Sex A, the initial weights have the same mean and variance as the final weights
      • Similarly in Sex B, the initial and final weights have the same distribution
      • This statistician concludes that, while any individual student's weight might change substantially over the course of the year, the gains and losses cancel each other and any overall effect is negligible. — It was 1967, so Lord used ANOVAs:
    l_a_anov = aov(Weight ~ Timepoint, filter(l_df_long, Sex == 'F'))
l_b_anov = aov(Weight ~ Timepoint, filter(l_df_long, Sex == 'M'))
Anova(l_a_anov)
    ## Anova Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: Weight
##           Sum Sq  Df F value Pr(>F)
## Timepoint      0   1       0  0.995
## Residuals  31589 998
    Anova(l_b_anov)
    ## Anova Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: Weight
##            Sum Sq  Df F value Pr(>F)
## Timepoint    14.5   1  0.4677 0.4942
## Residuals 30881.4 998

    But we can do an equivalent thing with a linear model:

    l_mod1 = lm(Gain ~ Sex, data = l_df)

    ANCOVA

    • The second statistician decides to control for the initial weight of the students
      • The slopes of the regression lines between initial and final weights are similar in the two dorms, which allows them to compare the intercepts with an ANCOVA:
    l_ancov = aov(Final ~ Sex + Initial, data = l_df)
Anova(l_ancov)
    ## Anova Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: Final
##            Sum Sq  Df F value    Pr(>F)    
## Sex         851.9   1  33.274 1.067e-08 ***
## Initial   13481.6   1 526.599 < 2.2e-16 ***
## Residuals 25524.4 997                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

    And indeed, it is clear from the graph that the two regression lines will have very different intercepts:

    In other words: Students in Sex B are gaining more weight than students in Sex B because for any given initial weight, the average final weight in Sex B is higher than Sex A.

    So, what is going on here?

    A Digression: Mediation

    Let's construct a different data set. In this data set students in Sex B will gain more weight than students in Sex B, and this gain will be mediated by initial weight. I.e., the more you weight initially, the more you gain.

    # Start with 1000 students
m_a_0 = rnorm(500, 150, 5)
m_b_0 = rnorm(500, 160, 5)

# Final weight (and therefore weight gain) solely a function of initial weight
m_a_f = (1+delt)*m_a_0 + rnorm(500, 0, 1)
m_b_f = (1+delt)*m_b_0 + rnorm(500, 0, 1)

m_df = data.frame(Sex = rep(c('F','M'), each = 500),
                Initial = c(m_a_0, m_b_0),
                Final = c(m_a_f, m_b_f),
                Gain = c(m_a_f - m_a_0, m_b_f - m_b_0))
head(m_df)
    ##   Sex  Initial    Final     Gain
## 1   F 156.2228 186.8056 30.58282
## 2   F 147.8403 177.5124 29.67215
## 3   F 150.0343 179.1848 29.15046
## 4   F 150.6228 179.4170 28.79424
## 5   F 147.9519 175.9447 27.99282
## 6   F 152.8171 183.9047 31.08763
    m_df_long = (m_df
           %>% select(-Gain)
           %>% gather(Timepoint, Weight, Initial, Final))

ggplot(m_df, aes(Initial, Final)) +
    geom_point(aes(colour = Sex), alpha = 0.3) +
    stat_ellipse(aes(colour = Sex)) +
    # geom_smooth(aes(colour = Sex), method = 'lm',
    #           se = FALSE) +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype = 2) +
    scale_colour_manual(values = cols)

    In this case, both groups of students are gaining weight, but that gain is only related to the initial weight. There is no direct effect of Sex.

    ANOVA

    Let's do what Lord's first hypothetical statistician did, and run an ANOVA:

    m_a_anov = aov(Weight ~ Timepoint, filter(m_df_long, Sex == 'F'))
m_b_anov = aov(Weight ~ Timepoint, filter(m_df_long, Sex == 'M'))

    When we don't control for initial weight, we see a clear effect of Sex.

    ANCOVA

    Now let's follow Lord's second statistician's method. Again. the slopes in the two groups are similar, so we are justified in comparing their intercepts.

    m_ancov = aov(Gain ~ Sex + Initial, data = m_df)
Anova(m_ancov)
    ## Anova Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: Gain
##            Sum Sq  Df  F value Pr(>F)    
## Sex          0.34   1   0.3165 0.5738    
## Initial    971.30   1 914.1465 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals 1059.33 997                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

    Effect of Sex is no longer significant!

    Linear model framework:

    m_mod2 = lm(Gain ~ Sex + Initial, data = m_df)

    The intercept and effect of Sex have both disappeared. Indeed, the intercepts of the two regression lines are the same.

    So, what happened here? Who is correct?

    Everyone is right; context is everything

    Statistician 1 is testing the total effect of sex on weight gain:

    \[ TE = E(G|S = 1) - E(G|S = 0) \]

    or

    \[ TE = (b + ac) - a \]

    \[ TE = b - a(1-c) \]

    Statistician 2 is testing the direct effect of sex on weight gain:

    \[ DE = \sum_w[E(G|S = 1, W_I = w) - E(G|S = 0, W_I = w)]P(W_I = w|S = 0) \]

    or

    \[ DE = b \]

    In this toy example we know that \(b = 0\), and it seems clear that Sex is a red herring. But that is less obvious in real life examples:

    • Poverty, toxins, cancer
      • what can you measure?
      • what info can clinicians access?
      • what policies are you trying to inform?

    The fact that the effect of X on Y is mediated by M doesn't mean that the effect is not real, or not important. Nor does it mean that M doesn't matter. It's all real.

    Connect Mediation back to Lord

    Lord's dataset can be thought of in the same way:

    In this case, \(b\) is not zero, but I chose values for \(b\), \(a\), and \(c\) such that \(b = a(1 - c)\) and therefore \(TE = 0\).

    You can see this more clearly if I plot Gain vs. \(W_I\), instead of \(W_F\) vs. \(W_I\) as Lord did:

    Which is what leads us to our different conclusions.

    \[ G \sim \beta_{10} + \beta_{11} * S \]

    The first statistician was testing the total effect of sex

    There is no need for the mediating variable to be the baseline value of the response variable. E.g.

    • Sex
    • Body fat % (not actually linear but never mind)
    • Cardiovascular disease
